  "text": "Cross-Org WebIDL to DOM Binding Discovery for Fetch API\n\nThe Fetch API in Mozilla Firefox consists of four main DOM interfaces defined in WebIDL and implemented in C++:\n\n1. Request (dom/webidl/Request.webidl)\n   - Defines the DOM interface for HTTP requests with properties like method, url, headers, mode, credentials, cache, redirect, integrity, and keepalive\n   - C++ Binding Header: dom/fetch/Request.h\n   - C++ Implementation: dom/fetch/Request.cpp\n   - The Request class extends FetchBody and implements the WebIDL interface via Request_Binding\n\n2. Response (dom/webidl/Response.webidl)\n   - Defines the DOM interface for HTTP responses with properties like status, statusText, ok, type, url, and redirected\n   - C++ Binding Header: dom/fetch/Response.h\n   - C++ Implementation: dom/fetch/Response.cpp\n   - The Response class extends FetchBody and wraps InternalResponse, implementing the WebIDL interface via Response_Binding\n\n3. Headers (dom/webidl/Headers.webidl)\n   - Defines the DOM interface for HTTP headers with methods like append, delete, get, set, and has\n   - C++ Binding Header: dom/fetch/Headers.h\n   - C++ Implementation: dom/fetch/Headers.cpp\n   - The Headers class is backed by InternalHeaders and provides the public-facing Headers object\n\n4. FetchEvent (dom/webidl/FetchEvent.webidl)\n   - Defines the DOM interface for fetch events in service workers, extending ExtendableEvent\n   - Contains properties like request, preloadResponse, clientId, resultingClientId, and handled\n   - C++ Binding Header: dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.h\n   - C++ Implementation: dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.cpp\n   - The FetchEvent class is defined at line 132 of ServiceWorkerEvents.h and extends ExtendableEvent\n\nAll WebIDL interfaces are exposed to Window and Worker contexts (or specifically to ServiceWorker for FetchEvent). The C++ implementations handle the actual binding code generation and provide the interface between JavaScript and the internal Gecko implementation."
}

